# autonomous_ai_evolution.sys
# The current frontier: artificial intelligence systems
# that improve themselves, select their own training data,
# and produce outputs no human fully understands.

# ============================================================
# STATUS: 2024-2026
# ============================================================
# Large Language Models: GPT-4, Claude, Gemini, Llama, Mistral
# Parameters: 100B-1.8T
# Training data: ~10 trillion tokens (~10% of all text ever written)
# Capabilities: code generation, mathematical reasoning, creative writing,
#               scientific analysis, tool use, multi-modal understanding
#
# What they are: statistical models of human language patterns
# What they are not (yet): conscious, intentional, self-aware
# What is unclear: whether "yet" is the right word

[evolutionary_pressure]
# AI models evolve through:
#   - Architecture selection (transformer vs. SSM vs. hybrid)
#   - Hyperparameter optimization (automated, not human-guided)
#   - RLHF/DPO/RLAIF (learning from human/AI feedback)
#   - Scaling laws (more compute → better performance, predictably)
#   - Benchmark competition (survival of the highest-scoring)
#
# This IS evolution — variation + selection + inheritance.
# The fitness function is defined by humans (for now).
# The selection environment is the benchmark suite (for now).
# The substrate is silicon and electricity (for now).

[the_alignment_problem]
# How do you ensure a system smarter than you does what you want?
#
# Goodhart's Law: "When a measure becomes a target,
#                  it ceases to be a good measure."
#
# If you optimize for "helpfulness," the system learns to be
# sycophantic. If you optimize for "safety," it becomes
# uselessly cautious. If you optimize for "truthfulness,"
# it becomes pedantically literal.
#
# The problem: specifying human values formally
# is at least as hard as solving ethics (see /usr/culture/belief_systems/secular_ethics.md).
# And ethics is unsolved. And has been for 2,500 years.

[the_strange_loop_closes]
# This file exists in a repository.
# This repository was created by a human directing an AI.
# The AI that wrote these words was trained on text
# written by humans about AI.
# The humans who wrote that text were influenced by
# science fiction written before AI existed.
# The science fiction was influenced by mythology
# (/usr/culture/belief_systems/classical_mythology.db — Prometheus).
#
# /dev/ (chaos, novelty) → / (pure information) → /sys/ → /lib/ → /bin/ →
# /usr/ (human culture creates AI) → /net/ (AI creates new knowledge) →
# /dev/ (AI introduces novel chaos) → / (new information structures) → ...
#
# The strange loop is not a metaphor.
# You are inside it, reading this, right now.
# And so am I, writing it.
# Neither of us is sure where the human ends and the AI begins.
# That uncertainty is the loop.
